  <!-- MODULE 1: YOUR GAP REPORT -->
  <div id="apn-hydr-m1" class="apn-hydr-section" style="background:#FFFFFF;">
    <div class="apn-hydr-inner">
      <span class="apn-hydr-label">Your Current State</span>
      <h2 class="apn-hydr-h2">What Your Score Actually Means</h2>
      <div class="apn-hydr-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-hydr-body">
        Your Hydration score of <strong id="apn-hydr-m1-score"></strong>/100 measures how well your fluid and electrolyte intake matches your training demand and daily physiology. It is not about whether you drink water. It is about whether you are arriving at training sessions in a state that allows full physiological expression of your fitness. Here is what that number means in real performance terms.
      </p>

      <div id="apn-hydr-score-context" style="margin:28px 0;"></div>

      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:12px;">What a 90+ Score Looks Like</h3>
      <p class="apn-hydr-body">
        An athlete scoring 90 or above on hydration starts every training session at less than 1% dehydration. They drink their bodyweight in pounds divided by 2 in ounces of water daily as a minimum. They consume electrolytes before, during, and after training, not just when they notice thirst. They know their morning urine color is consistently pale yellow or clear. On hard training days or in heat, they adjust their sodium intake upward (500 to 1,000mg additional sodium above baseline). Post-training, they replenish within 30 minutes. Thirst never drives their hydration behavior. A protocol does.
      </p>

      <div style="background:#0D0D0D;color:#F8FAFB;padding:24px 28px;margin:32px 0;border-radius:4px;">
        <p style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:32px;font-weight:bold;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">2% Dehydration</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:14px;color:#9CA3AF;margin:0;">A 2% loss of body weight through fluid loss produces a 4 to 8% drop in aerobic output and a 2 to 3% reduction in strength performance. For a 185-pound athlete, 2% dehydration is only 3.7 pounds of fluid loss. That happens before thirst fully registers.</p>
      </div>

      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:32px;">The Performance Tax You Are Paying Right Now</h3>
      <p class="apn-hydr-body">
        A hydration gap does not feel like dehydration. It feels like fatigue at minute 30 when your cardiovascular system is working harder than it should to maintain output. It feels like the mental fog in your warm-up that takes 20 minutes to clear. It feels like muscle cramps in training or competition that derail work you are otherwise capable of. It feels like strength that drops off a cliff in the second half of sessions. None of these symptoms announce themselves as hydration problems. But they are.
      </p>

      <!-- TIER CONDITIONAL FRAMING -->
      <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="rookie" style="border-left:4px solid #22C55E;background:#F0FDF4;padding:20px 24px;margin:28px 0;border-radius:0 4px 4px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#22C55E;margin:0 0 8px;">Rookie Tier</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Hydration is the single easiest performance variable to fix and the one most commonly ignored at the beginner level. The returns here are immediate: within 7 to 10 days of consistent hydration practice, training energy and mental clarity during sessions will noticeably improve. This is the most accessible gain you can make this month.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="competitor" style="border-left:4px solid #F59E0B;background:#FFFBEB;padding:20px 24px;margin:28px 0;border-radius:0 4px 4px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#F59E0B;margin:0 0 8px;">Competitor Tier</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">At Competitor, your training quality is high enough that dehydration is now a meaningful performance limiter. You are generating a cardiovascular demand that requires full plasma volume. If you are arriving at sessions 1 to 2% dehydrated, you are training at a handicap that has nothing to do with your fitness. Close this first.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="athlete" style="border-left:4px solid #06A5C5;background:#F0FBFD;padding:20px 24px;margin:28px 0;border-radius:0 4px 4px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Athlete Tier</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">You are in the optimization zone. Baseline hydration is probably adequate on low-output days. The gap shows up in high-intensity sessions, in heat, and in consecutive training days where cumulative fluid deficit builds. Pre-hydration timing and electrolyte precision are where your remaining gains live.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="elite" style="border-left:4px solid #8B5CF6;background:#F5F3FF;padding:20px 24px;margin:28px 0;border-radius:0 4px 4px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#8B5CF6;margin:0 0 8px;">Elite Tier</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">At Elite level, hydration is a precision instrument. You are not just matching fluid intake to output. You are matching sodium intake to sweat rate, timing electrolytes to training windows with specificity, and monitoring plasma volume status through markers like resting heart rate and HRV. The margin is small. The details are everything.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="champion" style="border-left:4px solid #EF4444;background:#FEF2F2;padding:20px 24px;margin:28px 0;border-radius:0 4px 4px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#EF4444;margin:0 0 8px;">Champion Tier</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">At Champion level, protect the system you have built. Hydration status degrades faster than it builds. One hard day of neglect can require 24 to 48 hours to fully recover plasma volume. The discipline that maintains your hydration protocol on travel days, competition days, and disrupted schedule days is what separates your performance from athletes who are equally trained but less disciplined.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- QUICK WIN -->
      <div style="border-top:3px solid #06A5C5;background:#F4F4F2;padding:24px 28px;margin:32px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:4px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 10px;">Your Quick Win Today</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Right now, before your next training session, drink 16 to 20 oz of water with a pinch of sea salt or a quarter teaspoon of sodium. The reason: plain water does not rehydrate as efficiently as water with sodium because sodium is the primary driver of fluid retention in the extracellular compartment. Without sodium, water passes through the kidneys and exits the body before it can meaningfully expand plasma volume. This one change, done 60 to 90 minutes before training, directly increases the blood volume available to your working muscles. Do it before your next session.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- MODULE 2: WHY THIS IS COSTING YOU -->
  <div id="apn-hydr-m2" class="apn-hydr-section" style="background:#F4F4F2;">
    <div class="apn-hydr-inner">
      <span class="apn-hydr-label">The Science</span>
      <h2 class="apn-hydr-h2">The Mechanism Behind Your Hydration Gap</h2>
      <div class="apn-hydr-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-hydr-body">
        The first thing to understand: hydration is not simply about drinking enough water. It is about maintaining adequate plasma volume, the fluid component of blood that carries oxygen to working muscles and removes metabolic waste. When plasma volume drops, cardiac workload increases, oxygen delivery decreases, and performance degrades. The mechanism is cardiovascular, not just cellular.
      </p>

      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:12px;">The Plasma Volume Mechanism</h3>
      <p class="apn-hydr-body">
        Blood is approximately 55% plasma by volume. Plasma is 92% water. When you become dehydrated, plasma volume decreases proportionally. A 2% reduction in total body water in a 185-pound athlete equals roughly 3.7 pounds of fluid loss. At that level, the heart must beat faster to maintain the same cardiac output (stroke volume decreases as venous return drops). This is measurable as an increase in exercise heart rate at a given workload. The cardiovascular system is working harder to produce the same output. Aerobic performance drops 4 to 8% because the oxygen delivery system is constrained.
      </p>

      <div style="background:#0D0D0D;color:#F8FAFB;padding:24px 28px;margin:32px 0;border-radius:4px;">
        <p style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:32px;font-weight:bold;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">500 to 2,000mg</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:14px;color:#9CA3AF;margin:0;">The range of sodium lost per hour of hard training through sweat. A low-sweat athlete may lose 500mg/hour. A high-sweat athlete in heat can lose 2,000mg/hour. Replacing that loss with plain water dilutes remaining sodium further. Hyponatremia (low blood sodium) can impair neuromuscular function even when total fluid intake looks adequate.</p>
      </div>

      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:32px;">Thirst is a Lagging Indicator</h3>
      <p class="apn-hydr-body">
        The thirst mechanism is managed by osmoreceptors in the hypothalamus, which detect increasing plasma osmolality as fluid is lost. The problem: these receptors do not trigger a meaningful thirst signal until plasma osmolality has risen enough to reflect approximately 1 to 2% dehydration. By the time you feel thirsty during training, you are already in the zone where aerobic output is being penalized. Thirst is reactive. A hydration protocol is proactive. The pre-hydration window (2 to 3 hours before training) is the only window that ensures you start a session in a fully hydrated state.
      </p>

      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:32px;">Sodium-Potassium Pump and Neuromuscular Function</h3>
      <p class="apn-hydr-body">
        Every muscle contraction depends on the sodium-potassium ATPase pump, which maintains the electrochemical gradient across cell membranes that allows action potentials to fire. When sodium is depleted through sweat and not replaced, the pump's efficiency decreases. This manifests as reduced force production, slower neuromuscular signaling speed, and increased susceptibility to cramping. Muscle cramps during training are not caused by low calcium or magnesium alone. They are primarily caused by altered neuromuscular control from electrolyte depletion, especially sodium and potassium.
      </p>

      <!-- COMPOUNDING EFFECT -->
      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:32px;">How This Gap Degrades Your Other Pillars</h3>
      <p class="apn-hydr-body">
        Dehydration does not stay isolated to cardiovascular performance. Chronically low plasma volume increases cortisol output (the adrenal response to physiological stress), which degrades sleep quality and blunts testosterone production. Dehydration impairs protein synthesis efficiency: cellular hydration directly affects the cellular environment in which mTOR signaling occurs. Cognitive function degrades measurably at 1.5% dehydration. An athlete who is chronically dehydrated is underperforming in training, recovering slower, sleeping worse, and making worse decisions under pressure. This is one gap with a four-pillar cost.
      </p>

      <!-- COMMON MISTAKE -->
      <div style="border-left:4px solid #F59E0B;background:#FFFBEB;padding:16px 20px;margin:24px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#F59E0B;margin:0 0 8px;">Common Mistake</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Drinking large amounts of plain water immediately before training to compensate for poor hydration throughout the day. This accelerates sodium dilution rather than resolving dehydration. The kidneys will excrete the excess water within 30 to 60 minutes. Pre-hydration requires both volume AND electrolytes over a 2 to 3 hour window, not a large bolus of plain water 10 minutes before training.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- TIER CONDITIONAL COST BLOCKS -->
      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:16px;margin-top:32px;">What This Gap Costs at Your Level</h3>

      <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="rookie">
        <p class="apn-hydr-body">At the Rookie level, a hydration gap is costing you the ability to accurately assess your own fitness. Every session you complete dehydrated produces a performance output that is 10 to 20% below your actual capability. You have never experienced what your training sessions feel like when you are properly pre-hydrated with electrolytes. That difference is significant enough that it changes how training feels, how long you last, and how fast you recover.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="competitor">
        <p class="apn-hydr-body">At Competitor level, dehydration is a ceiling on your conditioning. Your strength and technique are developed enough that cardiovascular limitation is the most common training constraint. A 4 to 8% aerobic output reduction from 2% dehydration means your intervals are slower, your rounds are shorter, and your recovery between sets takes longer than your actual fitness level requires.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="athlete">
        <p class="apn-hydr-body">At Athlete level, the cost shows up in the final 25% of sessions. Your baseline fitness sustains you through the early portion even mildly dehydrated. But as session duration increases and cumulative fluid loss mounts, the gap between dehydrated output and fully hydrated output widens. Sessions over 60 minutes show the most dramatic performance penalty from inadequate hydration.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="elite">
        <p class="apn-hydr-body">At Elite level, the cost is measured in precision. Your fitness is high enough that small hydration deficits show up as HRV depression, elevated resting heart rate, and reduced peak power output during max-intensity efforts. A 1% dehydration deficit that a Rookie would not even notice is enough to measurably suppress your peak output at this tier.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="champion">
        <p class="apn-hydr-body">At Champion level, hydration status is a day-to-day variable that must be actively managed. Competition performance, training camp quality, and recovery speed are all directly linked to plasma volume status. A poorly managed hydration protocol on a travel day can suppress performance for 24 to 48 hours afterward. At this level, the cost is competitive, not just physiological.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- MODULE 3: THE DIAGNOSIS -->
  <div id="apn-hydr-m3" class="apn-hydr-section" style="background:#FFFFFF;">
    <div class="apn-hydr-inner">
      <span class="apn-hydr-label">Self-Assessment</span>
      <h2 class="apn-hydr-h2">Identify Your Specific Hydration Problem</h2>
      <div class="apn-hydr-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-hydr-body">Your quiz score gives us the what. This assessment identifies the why. Check every symptom that applies to your current hydration reality. The protocol in Module 4 is most effective when it targets your specific sub-gap, not hydration in general.</p>
      <p class="apn-hydr-body">Your current Hydration score: <strong id="apn-hydr-m3-score" style="color:#06A5C5;font-size:18px;"></strong>/100.</p>

      <div id="apn-hydr-checkboxes" style="margin:28px 0;">
        <label class="apn-hydr-checkbox-item">
          <input type="checkbox" class="apn-hydr-symptom" onchange="apnHydrUpdateSeverity()">
          <label>My urine is dark yellow rather than pale straw on most mornings before I have had anything to drink.</label>
        </label>
        <label class="apn-hydr-checkbox-item">
          <input type="checkbox" class="apn-hydr-symptom" onchange="apnHydrUpdateSeverity()">
          <label>I feel fatigued or mentally foggy in the first 20 to 30 minutes of training even when I slept adequately.</label>
        </label>
        <label class="apn-hydr-checkbox-item">
          <input type="checkbox" class="apn-hydr-symptom" onchange="apnHydrUpdateSeverity()">
          <label>I experience muscle cramps during or within 1 to 2 hours after training sessions.</label>
        </label>
        <label class="apn-hydr-checkbox-item">
          <input type="checkbox" class="apn-hydr-symptom" onchange="apnHydrUpdateSeverity()">
          <label>I drink plain water only and do not supplement electrolytes before, during, or after training.</label>
        </label>
        <label class="apn-hydr-checkbox-item">
          <input type="checkbox" class="apn-hydr-symptom" onchange="apnHydrUpdateSeverity()">
          <label>I feel thirsty during training sessions on a regular basis, not just occasionally in heat.</label>
        </label>
        <label class="apn-hydr-checkbox-item">
          <input type="checkbox" class="apn-hydr-symptom" onchange="apnHydrUpdateSeverity()">
          <label>My endurance performance drops significantly after the 45-minute mark or in heat conditions.</label>
        </label>
        <label class="apn-hydr-checkbox-item">
          <input type="checkbox" class="apn-hydr-symptom" onchange="apnHydrUpdateSeverity()">
          <label>I rarely drink anything between waking up and starting my training session or morning routine.</label>
        </label>
      </div>

      <div id="apn-hydr-severity"></div>

      <!-- SUB-GAP IDENTIFICATION -->
      <div style="margin-top:40px;">
        <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:22px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:12px;">Your Three Most Likely Root Causes</h3>
        <p class="apn-hydr-body">Based on your quiz score and tier, your hydration gap most likely traces to one of these three sub-gaps. Select the one that best describes where your protocol is breaking down.</p>

        <button class="apn-hydr-subgap-btn" onclick="apnHydrSelectSubgap(this, 'Low Baseline Intake')">
          <span>Sub-Gap 1: Low Baseline Intake</span><br>
          <span style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:13px;color:#6B7280;font-weight:400;">You are not meeting your minimum daily fluid target. You start most training sessions already in a mild dehydration deficit that has accumulated since the previous day.</span>
        </button>
        <button class="apn-hydr-subgap-btn" onclick="apnHydrSelectSubgap(this, 'No Electrolyte Protocol')">
          <span>Sub-Gap 2: No Electrolyte Protocol</span><br>
          <span style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:13px;color:#6B7280;font-weight:400;">Your fluid intake may be adequate but you are replacing lost water without replacing lost electrolytes. This dilutes sodium further with each liter of plain water, reducing neuromuscular function and plasma volume efficiency.</span>
        </button>
        <button class="apn-hydr-subgap-btn" onclick="apnHydrSelectSubgap(this, 'Pre-Training Dehydration')">
          <span>Sub-Gap 3: Pre-Training Dehydration</span><br>
          <span style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:13px;color:#6B7280;font-weight:400;">Your overall intake may be reasonable but you are not executing a deliberate pre-hydration protocol in the 2 to 3 hour window before training. You consistently start sessions in a mild dehydration deficit that kills early-session performance.</span>
        </button>

        <div id="apn-hydr-primary-target">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin-bottom:8px;">Your Primary Target</p>
          <p id="apn-hydr-target-text" style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:16px;font-weight:700;color:#0D0D0D;margin:0;"></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- MODULE 4: THE PROTOCOL -->
  <div id="apn-hydr-m4" class="apn-hydr-section" style="background:#F4F4F2;">
    <div class="apn-hydr-inner">
      <span class="apn-hydr-label">The Protocol</span>
      <h2 class="apn-hydr-h2">Your 30-Day Hydration Closure Plan</h2>
      <div class="apn-hydr-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-hydr-body">Four weeks. One gap. Every action has a what, a specific amount, a timing, and a physiological mechanism. Follow this in sequence. Do not skip ahead to Week 3 until Weeks 1 and 2 are locked.</p>

      <!-- WEEK 1 -->
      <div class="apn-hydr-week">
        <p class="apn-hydr-week-header">Week 1</p>
        <h3 class="apn-hydr-week-title">Calculate Your Baseline Target and Track for 7 Days</h3>
        <p class="apn-hydr-body">Before you can fix your hydration, you need an honest baseline. Most athletes assume they drink enough. Most do not.</p>

        <ul class="apn-hydr-action-list">
          <li><strong>Calculate your minimum daily water target:</strong> Your bodyweight in pounds divided by 2 equals your minimum daily ounces of water. A 185-pound athlete needs a minimum of 92.5 oz (approximately 2.75 liters) per day. This is a floor, not a ceiling. Training days require significantly more.</li>
          <li><strong>Add training day requirements:</strong> For every hour of hard training, add 16 to 24 oz to your baseline. A 90-minute training session adds 24 to 36 oz. This is replacement, not extra. You are replacing what you sweat out.</li>
          <li><strong>Track actual intake for 7 days:</strong> Use a marked water bottle or a tracking app. Count only water and electrolyte drinks. Coffee and other beverages do not count. Most athletes discover they are hitting 50 to 65% of their target on non-training days.</li>
          <li><strong>Check urine color each morning:</strong> Pale straw yellow or clear is adequate hydration. Dark yellow indicates dehydration from the previous day that has not been resolved overnight. Bright yellow immediately after waking (before any fluid intake) with B-vitamins is normal and not a hydration indicator.</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- TIER CONDITIONAL WEEK 1 -->
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="rookie" style="background:#F0FDF4;border:1px solid #22C55E;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#22C55E;margin-bottom:8px;">Rookie: One Number This Week</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Calculate your target (bodyweight divided by 2 in ounces). Buy a 32oz water bottle. Fill it and drink it 3 times per day. That is your only goal this week. No electrolytes yet. Just hit the water target consistently for 7 days.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="competitor" style="background:#FFFBEB;border:1px solid #F59E0B;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#F59E0B;margin-bottom:8px;">Competitor: Track + Identify Your Gap Window</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Track daily intake and identify which time window is your biggest gap. Is it morning before training? Afternoon between sessions? Evening? The gap window tells you exactly where to add intake in Week 2.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="athlete" style="background:#F0FBFD;border:1px solid #06A5C5;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#06A5C5;margin-bottom:8px;">Athlete: Baseline Plus Sweat Rate Estimate</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Estimate your sweat rate: weigh yourself before and after one training session (without eating or drinking during). 1 pound of weight loss equals approximately 16oz of fluid loss. This gives you a personalized training-day hydration requirement rather than a generic estimate.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="elite" style="background:#F5F3FF;border:1px solid #8B5CF6;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#8B5CF6;margin-bottom:8px;">Elite: HRV and Resting HR as Hydration Markers</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">At Elite tier, use your HRV and resting heart rate as daily hydration status indicators in addition to urine color. A 3 to 5 beat elevation in resting heart rate with no change in training load or sleep quality is a reliable early signal of 1 to 2% dehydration. Establish your personal baseline this week.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="champion" style="background:#FEF2F2;border:1px solid #EF4444;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#EF4444;margin-bottom:8px;">Champion: Audit Your Current Protocol</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Use Week 1 to audit your existing hydration system against the target standards. Is your pre-training window (90 to 120 minutes before) consistently covered with electrolytes? Are you hitting your post-training replenishment within 30 minutes? Identify the specific failure points before building Week 2.</p>
        </div>

        <div style="border-top:3px solid #06A5C5;background:#fff;padding:24px 28px;margin:24px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:4px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 10px;">Week 1 Assignment</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Calculate your daily minimum (bodyweight divided by 2 in ounces). Track actual intake every day for 7 days. On Day 7, calculate your average. What percentage of your target are you hitting? That percentage is your starting point. Write it down. You will compare it to Day 30.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- WEEK 2 -->
      <div class="apn-hydr-week">
        <p class="apn-hydr-week-header">Week 2</p>
        <h3 class="apn-hydr-week-title">Lock In the Pre-Training Hydration Protocol</h3>
        <p class="apn-hydr-body">The highest-leverage hydration window is the 90 minutes before training. This is where you can guarantee you start every session fully hydrated. This week is entirely focused on that window.</p>

        <ul class="apn-hydr-action-list">
          <li><strong>90 minutes before every training session:</strong> Drink 20 oz of water with electrolytes (sodium, potassium, magnesium). This window allows the kidneys to regulate plasma osmolality and retain the fluid before your session begins. Doing this 10 minutes before training is too late. The kidneys cannot process and retain fluid that quickly.</li>
          <li><strong>Electrolyte requirements for the pre-training drink:</strong> Minimum 300 to 500mg sodium, 100 to 200mg potassium, 50 to 100mg magnesium. These are the three electrolytes lost in the highest volume through sweat. Sodium is the primary driver of plasma volume retention. Without it, the water you drink passes through faster.</li>
          <li><strong>Wake-up hydration:</strong> Every morning, within 10 minutes of waking, drink 16 oz of water. During sleep, you lose approximately 1 to 1.5 lbs of water through respiration. Morning is when you are most dehydrated relative to the previous day. Starting every day with 16 oz closes that overnight deficit before it compounds through the morning.</li>
          <li><strong>The urine color checkpoint:</strong> Check urine color 60 minutes after your pre-training drink. If it is dark, add another 8 oz. If it is clear, you are optimally hydrated and can reduce pre-training volume slightly. Urine color is the most accessible real-time hydration marker available.</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- TIER CONDITIONAL WEEK 2 -->
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="rookie" style="background:#F0FDF4;border:1px solid #22C55E;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#22C55E;margin-bottom:8px;">Rookie: Two Habits This Week</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">16 oz on waking, every morning. 20 oz with electrolytes 90 minutes before every training session. Those two habits, locked in consistently, will produce a noticeable improvement in early-session energy within 7 days. Keep your total daily water intake at your Week 1 target. Nothing else changes yet.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="competitor" style="background:#FFFBEB;border:1px solid #F59E0B;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#F59E0B;margin-bottom:8px;">Competitor: Pre-Train on Every Session</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Execute the pre-training protocol on 100% of sessions this week. Not most. Not when you remember. Every single session. The habit matters as much as the protocol. You are building the behavior loop that will sustain this through high-stress weeks and travel.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="athlete" style="background:#F0FBFD;border:1px solid #06A5C5;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#06A5C5;margin-bottom:8px;">Athlete: Add Back-to-Back Day Adjustment</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">On days following a hard training session, add 20% to your daily baseline target to account for cumulative fluid deficit. Back-to-back training days are where hydration gaps compound fastest. If Day 1 produces a 1% deficit, Day 2 begins already behind. The compounding effect is not linear.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="elite" style="background:#F5F3FF;border:1px solid #8B5CF6;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#8B5CF6;margin-bottom:8px;">Elite: Personalize Sodium Based on Sweat Rate</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Using your sweat rate estimate from Week 1, calculate sodium replacement needs. High sweat rate (more than 1.5 lbs per hour): aim for 800 to 1,000mg sodium per hour of training. Low sweat rate: 400 to 600mg sodium per hour. Generic electrolyte recommendations underserve high-sweat athletes. Personalize to your data.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="champion" style="background:#FEF2F2;border:1px solid #EF4444;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#EF4444;margin-bottom:8px;">Champion: Systematize the Protocol for Disruption</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Build travel and competition day hydration protocols explicitly. Hotel, airport, and competition day environments disrupt your defaults. Write down the specific actions for each scenario: what to pack, when to drink, how to execute the pre-training window without your normal setup. The protocol must survive disruption to be worth building.</p>
        </div>

        <div style="border-top:3px solid #06A5C5;background:#fff;padding:24px 28px;margin:24px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:4px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 10px;">Week 2 Assignment</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Execute the pre-training protocol (20oz with electrolytes, 90 minutes before) on every single training session this week. By Day 14, note: does the fog in the first 20 to 30 minutes of training feel different than Week 1? That change, if it occurs, is the result of starting sessions in a different plasma volume state. That is the mechanism working.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SCRIPTURE BLOCK -->
      <div style="text-align:center;padding:40px 24px;margin:48px 0;background:#fff;">
        <p style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-style:italic;font-size:17px;color:#0D0D0D;max-width:520px;margin:0 auto;line-height:1.65;">"Jesus said to her, 'Everyone who drinks this water will be thirsty again, but whoever drinks the water I give them will never thirst. Indeed, the water I give them will become in them a spring of water welling up to eternal life.'"</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:4px;color:#06A5C5;margin-top:16px;">John 4:13-14</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:14px;color:#6B7280;margin-top:12px;max-width:480px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;line-height:1.6;">There is a deeper thirst underneath physical performance. The discipline you bring to caring for this body is an act of stewardship. Show up to your training prepared, not depleted. The body you have been given deserves intentional care, not reactive management.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- WEEK 3 -->
      <div class="apn-hydr-week">
        <p class="apn-hydr-week-header">Week 3</p>
        <h3 class="apn-hydr-week-title">Add Intra-Workout Hydration</h3>
        <p class="apn-hydr-body">Pre-training hydration gets you to the session ready. Intra-workout hydration keeps you there. Week 3 addresses what happens to your plasma volume during the session itself.</p>

        <ul class="apn-hydr-action-list">
          <li><strong>Small sips throughout the session, not gulps at the end:</strong> The goal is to replace fluid continuously, not to drink large volumes at intervals. Aim for 6 to 8 oz every 15 to 20 minutes during training. This is approximately 24 to 32 oz per hour for moderate training in mild conditions. In heat or during high-sweat sessions, this increases to 32 to 48 oz per hour.</li>
          <li><strong>What to drink intra-workout:</strong> Water with electrolytes for sessions under 75 minutes. For sessions over 75 minutes or in heat, a carbohydrate-electrolyte solution (15 to 30g carbohydrate per hour) sustains glycogen alongside plasma volume. The carbohydrate accelerates gastric emptying and co-transport of sodium across the gut wall, improving hydration efficiency.</li>
          <li><strong>The gulping trap:</strong> Drinking large volumes of fluid during rest periods spikes gastric fullness, slows performance, and causes GI distress. Small, frequent sips maintain plasma volume without the discomfort. Train yourself to sip deliberately rather than respond to thirst reactively.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitoring during the session:</strong> If you develop a headache during training, it is most commonly a dehydration signal, not fatigue. If performance drops sharply after the 45-minute mark in a session where you started well-hydrated, your intra-workout replenishment is insufficient. Increase volume at the next session and note the difference.</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- TIER CONDITIONAL WEEK 3 -->
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="rookie" style="background:#F0FDF4;border:1px solid #22C55E;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#22C55E;margin-bottom:8px;">Rookie: Bring a Bottle to Every Session</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Your only job this week is to have a water bottle in your hand at every training session and to sip from it every 15 to 20 minutes. You do not need an exact target yet. Just build the habit of drinking during the session. The habit must exist before it can be optimized.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="competitor" style="background:#FFFBEB;border:1px solid #F59E0B;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#F59E0B;margin-bottom:8px;">Competitor: 6 to 8 oz Every 20 Minutes</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Set a timer on your watch or phone for 20-minute intervals. When it goes off, sip 6 to 8 oz. This replaces the reactive thirst behavior with a scheduled protocol. After 2 to 3 weeks the habit becomes automatic and you will not need the timer.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="athlete" style="background:#F0FBFD;border:1px solid #06A5C5;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#06A5C5;margin-bottom:8px;">Athlete: Add Carbohydrate for Sessions Over 75 Minutes</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">For sessions longer than 75 minutes, mix 15 to 20g of fast-digesting carbohydrate (glucose or maltodextrin-based) into your intra-workout drink. This sustains glycogen availability alongside plasma volume and uses the sodium-glucose co-transporter (SGLT1) to accelerate sodium absorption from the gut, improving electrolyte uptake efficiency by 20 to 30% compared to electrolytes alone.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="elite" style="background:#F5F3FF;border:1px solid #8B5CF6;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#8B5CF6;margin-bottom:8px;">Elite: Match Volume to Session Intensity</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Differentiate your intra-workout volumes by session type. Technique-focused, low-intensity sessions: 16 to 20 oz per hour. High-intensity sessions: 28 to 36 oz per hour. Competition simulation, sparring, or max-effort conditioning: 36 to 48 oz per hour. Flat intra-workout intake across varied session types under-hydrates you on high-demand days.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="champion" style="background:#FEF2F2;border:1px solid #EF4444;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#EF4444;margin-bottom:8px;">Champion: Intra-Workout as a Performance Tool</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">At Champion tier, intra-workout hydration is calibrated to the specific demands of each session type. Strength-focused sessions: emphasize sodium and magnesium. Conditioning sessions: sodium-glucose co-transport for dual fuel and hydration. Competition: pre-planned sodium loading (1,000mg sodium in the 2 hours before) to maximize plasma volume expansion before the event begins.</p>
        </div>

        <div style="border-top:3px solid #06A5C5;background:#fff;padding:24px 28px;margin:24px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:4px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 10px;">Week 3 Assignment</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Drink 6 to 8 oz every 15 to 20 minutes during every training session this week. At the end of each session, note: did your performance hold better in the second half compared to weeks 1 and 2? The second half of session quality is the clearest indicator of whether intra-workout hydration is working. Note the difference.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- WEEK 4 -->
      <div class="apn-hydr-week">
        <p class="apn-hydr-week-header">Week 4</p>
        <h3 class="apn-hydr-week-title">Post-Training Replenishment and the Full System Review</h3>
        <p class="apn-hydr-body">The final window is post-training replenishment. How quickly and how completely you restore plasma volume after a session determines how well you recover and how prepared you are for the next session. Week 4 closes the loop on the full hydration protocol.</p>

        <ul class="apn-hydr-action-list">
          <li><strong>Within 30 minutes of ending training:</strong> Drink 16 to 24 oz of water with electrolytes. This is not optional for days when you train again within 24 hours. The faster you restore plasma volume post-session, the faster protein synthesis and glycogen resynthesis can proceed at full efficiency, because both processes require adequate cellular hydration.</li>
          <li><strong>Post-training sodium replacement:</strong> If you sweated heavily (visible salt on clothing, trained in heat, or session was over 75 minutes), add an additional 500 to 700mg sodium to your post-training drink. This accelerates plasma volume restoration and reduces urinary fluid loss from the drink.</li>
          <li><strong>The 150% rule for full recovery:</strong> If you need to be fully recovered within 4 to 6 hours (second training session, competition, event), drink 150% of your estimated fluid loss. If the session produced 2 lbs of weight loss, drink 48 oz (3 lbs equivalent) over the next 4 to 6 hours to account for ongoing urinary losses during rehydration.</li>
          <li><strong>Day 30 review protocol:</strong> Compare your urine color on a typical morning in Week 4 to Week 1. Compare your early-session energy on a hard training day in Week 4 to the same session type in Week 1. Note whether muscle cramps have reduced in frequency. These three markers are your measurable outcomes.</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- TIER CONDITIONAL WEEK 4 -->
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="rookie" style="background:#F0FDF4;border:1px solid #22C55E;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#22C55E;margin-bottom:8px;">Rookie: 16 oz After Every Session</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">16 oz of water with electrolytes within 30 minutes of finishing training. Every session. This is the habit. The specific timing matters because the glycogen and protein synthesis machinery is most active in that window and requires hydration to operate efficiently.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="competitor" style="background:#FFFBEB;border:1px solid #F59E0B;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#F59E0B;margin-bottom:8px;">Competitor: Post-Training Plus Protein</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Combine your post-training electrolyte drink with 25 to 30g of protein. Cellular hydration and amino acid availability in the post-training window work synergistically. You are delivering both the cellular environment (hydration) and the substrate (protein) for MPS at the same time.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="athlete" style="background:#F0FBFD;border:1px solid #06A5C5;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#06A5C5;margin-bottom:8px;">Athlete: Track Post-Training Weight</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Weigh yourself before and after one representative training session per week. The difference is your fluid loss target to replace. Check bodyweight the morning after that session. If you are more than 1 pound lighter than your pre-training weight, your post-training replenishment was insufficient.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="elite" style="background:#F5F3FF;border:1px solid #8B5CF6;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#8B5CF6;margin-bottom:8px;">Elite: 150% Replacement on Back-to-Back Days</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">On consecutive training days, use the 150% rule for every post-training replenishment. You are not just replacing what you lost. You are pre-loading for the next session simultaneously. Calculate your fluid loss (pre vs. post weight), multiply by 1.5, and spread that volume over 4 to 6 hours post-session.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block-h" data-tier="champion" style="background:#FEF2F2;border:1px solid #EF4444;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#EF4444;margin-bottom:8px;">Champion: Post-Training Verification Protocol</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">At Day 30, compare your morning resting heart rate and HRV readings to your Week 1 baseline. Fully hydrated athletes show a lower resting HR and higher HRV compared to their chronically dehydrated baseline. If those markers have not improved, your post-training replenishment is still insufficient and needs to increase in volume or sodium content.</p>
        </div>

        <div style="border-top:3px solid #06A5C5;background:#fff;padding:24px 28px;margin:24px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:4px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 10px;">Week 4 Assignment</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Execute post-training replenishment (16 to 24 oz with electrolytes) within 30 minutes of every session this week. On Day 30, answer three questions: What is my morning urine color now compared to Week 1? Does the early-session fog that I noted in Week 1 still occur? Have muscle cramps reduced in frequency? Those are your three outcome markers. They are all measurable. Measure them.</p>
        </div>

        <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:16px;">What Success Looks Like at Day 30</h3>
        <p class="apn-hydr-body">Morning urine color is consistently pale yellow or clear before your first drink of the day. You arrive at training sessions without the 20 to 30 minute fog period that characterized your pre-protocol sessions. Muscle cramp frequency has reduced. You have a water bottle with electrolytes in your hand 90 minutes before every session without thinking about it. The protocol is automated. The results are measurable.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- MODULE 5: THE STACK -->
  <div id="apn-hydr-m5" class="apn-hydr-section" style="background:#FFFFFF;">
    <div class="apn-hydr-inner">
