        <div style="display:grid;gap:12px;margin-top:16px;">
          <div style="background:#F8F8F8;padding:14px 16px;border-radius:3px;">
            <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin-bottom:6px;">The Mechanism</p>
            <p class="apn-hydr-product-meta">Sodium is the primary extracellular electrolyte and the main driver of plasma volume regulation. When sodium intake matches sweat loss, the kidneys retain fluid in the vascular space rather than excreting it as urine. Potassium maintains the intracellular electrochemical gradient required for the sodium-potassium ATPase pump, which drives every muscle contraction. Magnesium is a cofactor for ATP synthesis and modulates muscle relaxation after contraction, directly addressing cramp susceptibility. A complete electrolyte panel addresses all three mechanisms simultaneously.</p>
