      <div style="border-left:4px solid #F59E0B;background:#FFFBEB;padding:16px 20px;margin:24px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#F59E0B;margin:0 0 8px;">Common Stack Mistake</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Using sugar-heavy sports drinks as your primary electrolyte source. Commercial sports drinks like Gatorade contain 21 to 34g of sugar per serving and relatively low sodium (110 to 160mg). For a high-sweat athlete losing 800 to 1,500mg sodium per hour, this is inadequate replacement. The sugar calories are also unnecessary for athletes not in the middle of endurance events. A purpose-formulated electrolyte powder delivers the electrolyte panel without the sugar load.</p>
